What is SNS ?
ans : SNS typically stands for "Social Networking Service," which refers to online platforms that allow people to connect and interact with each other.
      Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) is a managed service that provides message delivery from publishers to subscribers
     (also known as producers and consumers).

Why do we use SNS ?
ans : We use SNS to connect and communicate with others, share information, and stay updated on the activities and interests of friends, family, or communities online.

What is an Amazon SNS function, and how we can configure it?
ans : Amazon SNS (Simple Notification Service) is a cloud service that enables message distribution to a distributed set of recipients. To configure it, you set up topics, 
      subscribe endpoints (like email or mobile devices), and publish messages to the topics.

Difference between Amazon SNS & Amazon SQS.
ans : Amazon SNS (Simple Notification Service) is used for sending messages to multiple subscribers, such as email, SMS, or other endpoints, 
    in a publish-subscribe model. Amazon SQS (Simple Queue Service) is a message queuing service that decouples the components of a cloud application, 
    allowing them to communicate asynchronously by sending and receiving messages.
   In simple terms, SNS is for broadcasting messages to multiple recipients, while SQS is for reliably storing and retrieving messages 
    between individual components.

What are the different delivery formats and transports in AWS SNS ?
ans : Multiple subscription types: Messages can be delivered to application-to-application (A2A) endpoints (Amazon SQS, Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, AWS Lambda, HTTPS) 
    as well as application-to-person (A2P) endpoints (SMS, mobile push, and email).

